history.content: 127+61C+161 sounds pretty nuts, especially if you're also putting a lot of time into recruiting. I'd also strongly consider putting off 161 until after you've taken 61C unless your understanding of 61C material is already pretty solid.

children.subject: Well I think Weaver's teaching it so 161 might be a little heavier on the 61c material than usual (can't speak to this personally). But 127+61c+161 is probably a fair amount more difficult than 170+188+186+R5B. 127 is pretty intensive on its own (depends on your math background I suppose) and 61c+161 is definitely a grind.

Do you think data 100 would be a better choice then? The reason I was leaning to 161 was because I want to take it before I graduate (in spring next year), but im planning to take 189, 174 and physics 7b in the spring, so my schedule is basically picking 2 classes out of 174, 161 and data 100 to take.

Hmm... okay in that case a lot will depend on how comfortable you are with the math-y classes. If you think you can handle 127 without struggling too much and you're already planning on taking 189 in the spring, then keeping 61c+161 might be the way to go. But even then I'd consider switching it with 7b/174/DS100 just in case systems programming isn't your thing.
Thank you! Have you taken 127? From what I could gather, the class is difficult, but the workload itself is lower than the likes of 170 or 126 or a regular weekly pset class.

Haven't taken 127, mostly just going off of friends' experiences so take this all with a grain of salt. But yeah if you feel that the workload is manageable and not too conceptually difficult then you're probably fine.
Would you say its more or less than 170+188+186+r5b? I know 161 involves some 61c material, but i've heard its only for the first few weeks.

history.content: How would this workload compare to my current workload of CS 170, CS 188 and CS 186 (with an R5B)?  I haven't decided between 161 and Data 100 yet, but I'm leaning towards 161 since Data 100 seems fairly self-studyable. I thought this semester was pretty manageable conceptually and workload-wise, only stressful while I was recruiting for the first couple months. I plan on recruiting in the fall (as early as possible).
